<subSubSection id="DC9170A229480977FC6A491FFA74FB72" pageId="19" pageNumber="1063" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9434232929480977FC6A491FFA74FB72" blockId="19.[809,1426,1093,1207]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1063">
<emphasis id="A6FFFF3B29480977FC6A491FFC4CFB9F" box="[809,938,1093,1114]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1063">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="A6FFFF3B29480977FA1B491FFA6CFB9F" box="[1368,1418,1093,1114]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1063">bufo</emphasis>
, toad and 
<emphasis id="A6FFFF3B29480977FCD8493EFC3DFBBC" box="[923,987,1124,1145]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1063">pellis</emphasis>
, animal skin. We propose this name because of the ornamentation of the aboral side of the test, which is reminiscent of the warty skin of a toad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
